{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"81ce70ca-28ad-49de-af74-4f490e658866","content":"Since this is a TUnit project (with `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`), you run it with `dotnet run` and use TUnit's `--treenode-filter` to filter by class. The tree node pattern is `Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`:\n\n```\ndotnet run --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThis matches any assembly/namespace, the `SmsNotificationTests` class, and all tests within it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b1e46c16-b91a-483e-808f-1b14761aa864","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run only the `SmsNotificationTests` class from this TUnit project. TUnit uses `dotnet run` (since the output type is `Exe`) rather than `dotnet test`. TUnit has its own filtering mechanism.\n\nFor TUnit, you filter tests using the `--filter` flag. The class filter syntax would be:\n\n```\ndotnet run --filter \"*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nOr using the TUnit-specific filter syntax. Let me think about TUnit's filtering...\n\nTUnit uses `dotnet run` as the test runner since the project has `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`. The filter syntax for TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` with a glob pattern like `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*`.\n\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the exact syntax. TUnit supports `--treenode-filter` for filtering by the tree structure (Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test), so a pattern like `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` would match the class across any assembly and namespace. Alternatively, TUnit also accepts `--filter` with MSTest/xUnit-style syntax like `ClassName=SmsNotificationTests`, though `--treenode-filter` is the primary filtering mechanism for this exe-based runner.","outputTokens":535},"id":"1e912f54-69ef-45a5-bb51-1412f8a63b74","timestamp":"2026-04-07T14:25:21.257Z","parentId":"e4d81287-0c28-4081-9e1c-e8229aa94161"}
